        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Maps redrawn again</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;"><strong>Summary: Israel has restricted Gazans to a fraction of their previous territory, citing the need to pressure Hamas.</strong></p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Since the ceasefire collapsed on March 18, Israel has made changes to Gaza‚Äôs map. It designates about <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-2-may-25-spotlight-h3-5-70-of-the-territory" target="_blank">70% of the territory</a> as a military ‚Äúred zone‚Äù or under evacuation. The United Nations reports that over 420,000 Palestinians have been displaced.
        </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Moreover, newer buffer zones are enforced, especially along Gaza‚Äôs borders with Israel and Egypt, to prevent incidents like the Hamas attack on October 7, 2023. Palestinians risk being shot if they enter this ‚Äúno-go zone.‚Äù The largest expansion is in southern Gaza‚Äôs Rafah, which extends north to Khan Younis and the newer Morag Corridor.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Humanitarians warn that these changes prohibit entry to critical infrastructure, including half of Gaza‚Äôs water wells and many health facilities. Israel said this was necessary to eliminate Hamas tunnels and prevent another attack. However, critics argue that these moves suggest a long-term occupation and violate international law.</p>
        </mj-text>
