          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
           South Korea's contentious political scene <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-2-may-25-worldwide-h1-6-has-added-a-twist" target="_blank">has added a twist</a> just over a month before its snap elections. Acting President Han Duck-soo has resigned his role to take up a ‚Äúbigger responsibility,‚Äù hinting at his intention to run for president. He is seen as a key conservative figure following President Yoon Suk Yeol's impeachment, and his goal is to unite the troubled political party. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Additionally, the opposition frontrunner, Lee Jae-myung, faces some judicial issues. The Supreme Court overturned his acquittal on election law violations, putting his eligibility at risk. The opposition leader can appeal the decision, but observers doubt the matter will be resolved before the June 3 vote.</p>
