        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/druze-religious-leader-israel-lebanon-syria-flags.png" alt="The Druze are a small, Arabic-speaking ethnoreligious group in Israel, Lebanon, and Syria" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
          <i>The Druze are a small, Arabic-speaking ethnoreligious group in Israel, Lebanon, and Syria. Credits: Getty Images</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">     
         The Druze are an <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-2-may-25-foundations-h1-8-arabic-speaking-ethnoreligious" target="_blank">Arabic-speaking ethnoreligious</a> group. Their faith originates from Ismaili Shia Islam in the 11th century and fuses Islamic teachings with aspects of Hinduism and other religions. Some beliefs include reincarnation and respect for figures from Islam, Christianity, and Judaism. The Druze do not accept converts and discourage interfaith marriage, which helps them maintain a unique identity.
        </p>
        
     
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         Druze communities mainly exist in Syria, Lebanon, Jordan, Israel, and the Golan Heights. Despite borders, strong connections persist among Druze groups in the region. About 20,000 Druze live in the Golan Heights, many rejecting Israeli citizenship. In Israel, around 150,000 Druze are citizens and often serve in the military. Some say they are portrayed as the ‚Äú model minority‚Äù in Israel by the media.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         Recently, Israel carried out a warning strike in Syria against an extremist group allegedly planning to attack Druze civilians in the town of Sahnaya, near Damascus. The Israeli government emphasized its commitment to protecting Druze communities, citing deep ties with Druze in Israel and Syria.</p>
         <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         Larger Druze populations reside in Syria and Lebanon, particularly in Sweida and Mount Lebanon. Their history shows resilience and a careful balance between integration and tradition.</p>
        </mj-text>
